"title": "8703: antinomianism",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "8703: antinomianism",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>A form of spiritual anarchy, which rejects the law as having any place in the Christian life, whether as instructor or as assessor.  Paul's teaching that Christians are free from the law is sometimes misunderstood as antinomian.  But Paul reveres God's law, and teaches believers, who are free from the law as a system of salvation, to keep it out of gratitude for salvation freely given, and because holiness as defined by the law is the Christian calling.</p>\n<h2>Antinomianism as a rejection of God's laws</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer2:20\">JER 2:20</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Prov29:18\">PRO 29:18</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer5:5\">JER 5:5</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Hos8:12\">HOS 8:12</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Pet2:10\">2PE 2:10</a></p>\n<h2>Various people described as antinomian</h2>\n<h3>Israel described as antinomian</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek20:13\">EZK 20:13</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod32:25\">EXO 32:25</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer2:23-Jer2:25\">JER 2:23–2:25</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Hos8:1\">HOS 8:1</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Zech7:11-Zech7:12\">ZEC 7:11–7:12</a></p>\n<h3>The ungodly described as antinomian</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jude1:4\">JUD 1:4</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Tim3:1-2Tim3:5\">2TI 3:1–3:5</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Pet2:13-2Pet2:15\">2PE 2:13–2:15</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jude1:8\">JUD 1:8</a></p>\n<h3>The antichrist described as antinomian</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Thess2:3-2Thess2:10\">2TH 2:3–2:10</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Dan7:25\">DAN 7:25</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Dan8:9-Dan8:12\">DAN 8:9–8:12</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Dan8:23-Dan8:25\">DAN 8:23–8:25</a> <em>The object of these prophecies, Antiochus Epiphanes, foreshadowed the antichrist in his behaviour.</em></p>\n<h2>Jesus Christ and his followers accused of antinomianism</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt11:19\">MAT 11:19</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt12:2\">MAT 12:2</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John9:16\">JHN 9:16</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts6:11-Acts6:14\">ACT 6:11–6:14</a></p>\n<h3>Jesus Christ came to fulfil the law, not abolish it</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt5:17-Matt5:19\">MAT 5:17–5:19</a></strong></p>\n<h2>Paul rejects antinomianism</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom6:1-Rom6:2\">ROM 6:1–6:2</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom3:31\">ROM 3:31</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom7:7\">ROM 7:7</a></p>\n<h2>Misunderstandings, by opponents and converts alike, about Paul's teaching on freedom from the law</h2>\n<h3>Paul accused of antinomianism</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts21:28\">ACT 21:28</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom3:8\">ROM 3:8</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom6:15\">ROM 6:15</a></p>\n<h3>Paul corrects the Corinthians' interpretation of his teaching as a licence for antinomianism</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor10:23\">1CO 10:23</a></strong> <em>The phrase “Everything is permissible” is probably the Corinthians' misinterpretation of Paul's teaching.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor5:1-1Cor5:8\">1CO 5:1–5:8</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor6:12-1Cor6:13\">1CO 6:12–6:13</a></p>\n<h2>Punishment of antinomians</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer6:19\">JER 6:19</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezra7:26\">EZR 7:26</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Amos2:4-Amos2:5\">AMO 2:4–2:5</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev22:15\">REV 22:15</a></p>",
